being a partner with a guy like
him, an extraordinary person,

00:48:29.640 --> 00:48:31.380
is actually quite high.

00:48:31.380 --> 00:48:34.050
So you have to swallow
a lot of things

00:48:34.050 --> 00:48:36.570
which may, under
normal circumstances,

00:48:36.570 --> 00:48:39.200
be something that you might
want to walk away from.

00:48:39.200 --> 00:48:41.690
And the reason is because
of the extraordinary moat

00:48:41.690 --> 00:48:43.820
that he has created.

00:48:43.820 --> 00:48:45.050
So that's just one example.

00:48:45.050 --> 00:48:46.780
I'll give you a
few other examples.

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:52.070
I know of a business where
the premier credit rating

00:48:52.070 --> 00:48:56.900
company in the country
resigned the assignment.

00:48:56.900 --> 00:48:57.500
Why?

00:48:57.500 --> 00:48:58.980
Because he's not cooperating.

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:00.750
He basically told
them, buzz off.

00:49:00.750 --> 00:49:04.320
I'm not going to give
you the information.

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:06.010
And if you remember,
Charlie Munger

00:49:06.010 --> 00:49:09.996
did pretty much the same
thing with the auditors

00:49:09.996 --> 00:49:11.230
in "Daily Journal."

00:49:11.230 --> 00:49:13.080
And he had a huge tiff
with the auditors.

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:15.260
That's the point I'm making.

00:49:15.260 --> 00:49:16.850
These guys have
what Charlie Munger

00:49:16.850 --> 00:49:19.130
called a lot of chutzpah.

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:20.780
They absolutely
don't give a shit

00:49:20.780 --> 00:49:22.530
about what anybody
else thinks about them.

00:49:22.530 --> 00:49:24.029
They think they're
absolutely right.

00:49:24.029 --> 00:49:26.840
And it reminds me of what
Charlie Munger has said, never

00:49:26.840 --> 00:49:29.754
underestimate a man who
overestimates himself.

00:49:29.754 --> 00:49:31.670
And all entrepreneurs
overestimate themselves.

00:49:31.670 --> 00:49:35.200
And overconfidence is a very
important aspect of capitalism.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:38.695
What I'm trying to distinguish
is between the dumb fanatics

00:49:38.695 --> 00:49:40.440
and the intelligent fanatics.

00:49:40.440 --> 00:49:41.940
And I gave a talk
sometime back when

00:49:41.940 --> 00:49:45.470
I made that distinction
where I profiled

00:49:45.470 --> 00:49:47.540
seven intelligent
fanatics from India.

00:49:47.540 --> 00:49:51.240
And I gave a kind
of a checklist as

00:49:51.240 --> 00:49:54.140
to how I think about intelligent
fanatics versus dumb fanatics.

00:49:54.140 --> 00:49:58.750
So one of them is debt
or risk management.

00:49:58.750 --> 00:50:00.930
So a dumb fanatic
would-- they're

00:50:00.930 --> 00:50:03.510
all overconfident whether
you're dumb or not.

00:50:03.510 --> 00:50:06.820
But they bet the bank.

00:50:06.820 --> 00:50:08.240
And sometimes they get lucky.

00:50:08.240 --> 00:50:09.807
Most of the time, they blow up.

00:50:09.807 --> 00:50:11.890
So they don't know anything
about risk management.

00:50:11.890 --> 00:50:15.380
Whereas an intelligent fanatic
would make a series of bets.

00:50:15.380 --> 00:50:18.310
He's, like, writing insurance.

00:50:18.310 --> 00:50:20.930
And many of those
bets will fail.

00:50:20.930 --> 00:50:23.280
But even if all
of them fail, that

00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:24.720
doesn't destroy the company.

00:50:24.720 --> 00:50:25.464
So that's one.

00:50:25.464 --> 00:50:27.130
The other is they
almost certainly don't

00:50:27.130 --> 00:50:28.338
rely on other people's money.

00:50:28.338 --> 00:50:29.910
They use their own capital.

00:50:29.910 --> 00:50:31.170
They don't borrow money.

00:50:31.170 --> 00:50:34.330
So they don't create
financial structures

00:50:34.330 --> 00:50:37.570
where they are dependent upon
the kindness of strangers

00:50:37.570 --> 00:50:38.240
over there.

00:50:38.240 --> 00:50:39.100
So I see that.

00:50:39.100 --> 00:50:42.160
I see fanaticism, when
combined with intelligence,

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:45.090
that combined together, makes
a very nice combination.

00:50:45.090 --> 00:50:47.880
You see that it's so rare.

00:50:47.880 --> 00:50:50.340
If you look at the history
of wealth creation,

00:50:50.340 --> 00:50:53.330
when you find this
fanaticism with intelligence

00:50:53.330 --> 00:50:55.360
and integrity-- when you
combine those three--

00:50:55.360 --> 00:50:58.829
and if you can get it along
with a reasonable business--

00:50:58.829 --> 00:51:00.370
and that's the point
I'm making here,

00:51:00.370 --> 00:51:03.410
which is the point that even
in commodity industries,

00:51:03.410 --> 00:51:05.240
some entrepreneurs
have the ability

00:51:05.240 --> 00:51:07.720
to carve out a niche which
is very hard to copy.

00:51:07.720 --> 00:51:10.090
And that niche is coming
from the fanaticism

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:11.580
of the entrepreneur.

00:51:11.580 --> 00:51:13.080
As it's a very smart person.

00:51:13.080 --> 00:51:15.610
And therefore, if you can
become partners with him

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:18.940
on favorable terms in terms
of valuation and all of that,

00:51:18.940 --> 00:51:23.470
then you can ignore a lot of
other things, which is what

00:51:23.470 --> 00:51:25.970
Elon Musk's ex-wife was saying.

00:51:25.970 --> 00:51:27.830
They are crazy in many ways.

00:51:27.830 --> 00:51:32.010
These guys-- or women-- they
are very nutty in many ways.

00:51:32.010 --> 00:51:35.205
But I think you should not
over-focus on those matters.

00:51:35.205 --> 00:51:38.420
You should only focus on the
track record-- what they do,

00:51:38.420 --> 00:51:42.202
how they run their
business operations.

00:51:42.202 --> 00:51:43.660
MALE SPEAKER: So
if I can just push

00:51:43.660 --> 00:51:45.793
that question a
little bit further--

00:51:45.793 --> 00:51:47.520
SANJAY BAKSHI: Yes, Soreb.

00:51:47.520 --> 00:51:51.130
MALE SPEAKER: So not to say
that there are no intelligent

00:51:51.130 --> 00:51:55.620
fanatics and so on, but to
borrow that phrase of whether

00:51:55.620 --> 00:51:59.170
it is actually a one-foot
hurdle versus a six-foot hurdle,

00:51:59.170 --> 00:51:59.730
so to say--

00:51:59.730 --> 00:52:00.670
SANJAY BAKSHI: It
doesn't have to be.

00:52:00.670 --> 00:52:03.110
You see, the point is if
you're going to-- what

00:52:03.110 --> 00:52:04.230
are we trying to do here?

00:52:04.230 --> 00:52:05.440
We're trying to
compound capital, right?

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:07.023
We are doing it
sitting in our offices

00:52:07.023 --> 00:52:08.650
in an air-conditioned
environment

00:52:08.650 --> 00:52:11.980
without stepping out or actually
[INAUDIBLE] try to become rich.

00:52:11.980 --> 00:52:13.590
So it shouldn't be easy.

00:52:13.590 --> 00:52:15.590
I don't think the
idea of compounding

00:52:15.590 --> 00:52:17.819
capital at superlative
rates of return

00:52:17.819 --> 00:52:20.110
over long periods of time
should become extraordinarily

00:52:20.110 --> 00:52:21.560
easy for anybody.

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:24.470
If it was, then those
returns will go away.

00:52:24.470 --> 00:52:27.290
So I don't think it
should be that easy.

00:52:27.290 --> 00:52:29.990
When Mr. Buffett talks
about one-foot hurdles,

00:52:29.990 --> 00:52:31.976
he's talking about
his ability to predict

00:52:31.976 --> 00:52:33.600
the fundamental
economics of a business

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:35.120
over a long period of time.

00:52:35.120 --> 00:52:37.790
And believe it or
not, many businesses

00:52:37.790 --> 00:52:40.210
that he has invested in
are actually quite complex.

00:52:40.210 --> 00:52:41.990
So for a lot of
people, the ability

00:52:41.990 --> 00:52:47.710
to understand supercar
insurance is actually

00:52:47.710 --> 00:52:49.050
very, very different.

00:52:49.050 --> 00:52:50.160
But he has done that.

00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:51.850
So he defines a
circle of competence

00:52:51.850 --> 00:52:54.200
and he tries to stay within
that circle of competence.

00:52:54.200 --> 00:52:57.740
And I think that's a
wonderful model to have.

00:52:57.740 --> 00:53:00.980
But to assume that you will
find very simple things

00:53:00.980 --> 00:53:05.360
to do all along, I think that's
something which I don't really

00:53:05.360 --> 00:53:06.270
believe in.

00:53:06.270 --> 00:53:07.850
AUDIENCE: I have a
two-part question.

00:53:07.850 --> 00:53:10.790
Why is it that the
stereotyping-- is

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:14.100
it correct or incorrect--
is often found in hindsight,

00:53:14.100 --> 00:53:15.640
with the benefit of hindsight.

00:53:15.640 --> 00:53:18.700
With the disparities that
you listed, all five of them,

00:53:18.700 --> 00:53:21.970
are there certain tips or
shortcuts, further shortcuts,

00:53:21.970 --> 00:53:25.680
which you can tell to
distinguish between what

00:53:25.680 --> 00:53:28.710
could be an incorrect
assessment of opportunities

00:53:28.710 --> 00:53:32.950
which the market could
correlate over time?

00:53:32.950 --> 00:53:35.250
Like, how would you distinguish
between luck and skill

00:53:35.250 --> 00:53:35.917
and define this?

00:53:35.917 --> 00:53:37.083
SANJAY BAKSHI: Track record.

00:53:37.083 --> 00:53:37.890
Track record.

00:53:37.890 --> 00:53:40.056
You're really looking at
the long-term track record.

00:53:40.056 --> 00:53:42.250
If it was all luck, then
over a period of time,

00:53:42.250 --> 00:53:45.120
that would go away, right?

00:53:45.120 --> 00:53:47.460
What I'm trying to
illustrate is the point

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:49.540
that there are these
patterns that play out.

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:50.760
What we're trying to
do is if we picked

00:53:50.760 --> 00:53:53.009
one-- I picked this one
heuristic, the representative.

00:53:53.009 --> 00:53:55.060
There are many others.

00:53:55.060 --> 00:53:57.330
I just picked one
and I tried to think

00:53:57.330 --> 00:54:00.470
about the various manifestations
in which it occurs,

00:54:00.470 --> 00:54:03.710
which creates tradable
opportunities for public market

00:54:03.710 --> 00:54:04.960
investors.

00:54:04.960 --> 00:54:08.545
What I found was that the
whole idea of labeling-- and I

00:54:08.545 --> 00:54:12.335
mentioned that some time ago,
that intelligent fanatic is

00:54:12.335 --> 00:54:13.145
just a label.

00:54:13.145 --> 00:54:19.440
To somebody else, it might
look like a freak person.

00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:23.190
But to somebody else, it could
be an intelligent fanatic.

00:54:23.190 --> 00:54:24.876
But what is the truth?

00:54:24.876 --> 00:54:26.125
The truth lies in the numbers.

00:54:26.125 --> 00:54:28.620
The truth lies in what
they actually accomplish.

00:54:28.620 --> 00:54:31.720
So what we're really
looking at is, for example,

00:54:31.720 --> 00:54:34.710
in an industry with sub-normal
profitability-- take airlines.

00:54:34.710 --> 00:54:37.160
We saw that-- there is
one company which has

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:39.720
extraordinary profitability.

00:54:39.720 --> 00:54:41.720
So we all question why,
why is that happening.

00:54:41.720 --> 00:54:44.940
Is this luck or is this skill?

00:54:44.940 --> 00:54:46.590
And to answer that,
you have to look

00:54:46.590 --> 00:54:48.312
at the record over a
long period of time.

00:54:48.312 --> 00:54:50.520
You have to look at the
track record of that business

00:54:50.520 --> 00:54:52.430
during periods when the
airline industry was

00:54:52.430 --> 00:54:53.900
going through a
horrible period of time.

00:54:53.900 --> 00:54:56.020
And if you do that for
Ryanair and for Southwest,

00:54:56.020 --> 00:54:59.160
you will find that they had some
unusual fundamental financial

00:54:59.160 --> 00:55:01.970
performance even during
periods when the entire airline

00:55:01.970 --> 00:55:04.400
industry in the world was
going through a terrible phase.

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:07.500
So you try to look for
exceptional, outstanding

00:55:07.500 --> 00:55:10.030
performance over
long periods of time.

00:55:10.030 --> 00:55:13.070
And then you attribute
that to luck or skill.

00:55:13.070 --> 00:55:14.970
And occasionally, you
will find that there

00:55:14.970 --> 00:55:16.530
is some skill out there.

00:55:16.530 --> 00:55:19.900
The beauty is that the market
is not able to distinguish that.

00:55:19.900 --> 00:55:22.800
The market has this
labeling problem.

00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:24.675
The market thinks, oh,
it's a crappy business

00:55:24.675 --> 00:55:26.174
because it's in the
airline industry

00:55:26.174 --> 00:55:27.730
and because Warren
Buffett says so.

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:31.220
Therefore it should not be
priced as a real good quality

00:55:31.220 --> 00:55:31.810
business.

00:55:31.810 --> 00:55:34.184
But if we ignore for the
moment, if you de-bias yourself,

00:55:34.184 --> 00:55:37.170
if you remove the name, the
label of the airline industry

00:55:37.170 --> 00:55:39.030
and think like a
Graham, who said,

00:55:39.030 --> 00:55:41.435
once, I want to be
completely unbiased.

00:55:41.435 --> 00:55:43.560
I don't want to even know
the name of the business,

00:55:43.560 --> 00:55:46.560
if you just look at the
actual objective data,

00:55:46.560 --> 00:55:48.800
you will find staggering
financial performance.

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:50.577
You won't know what
the industry is.

00:55:50.577 --> 00:55:53.160
Just because you know that the
industry is an airline industry

00:55:53.160 --> 00:55:55.326
and there is this label
hovering around in your head

00:55:55.326 --> 00:55:57.630
that airlines are,
generally speaking--

00:55:57.630 --> 00:56:00.160
and that's a correct
label-- crappy businesses,

00:56:00.160 --> 00:56:03.180
you tend to misjudge
what you are seeing.

00:56:03.180 --> 00:56:06.172
And I think that's a bias
that is worth getting out of,

00:56:06.172 --> 00:56:07.630
because that's an
exploitable bias.

00:56:07.630 --> 00:56:10.790
That's a bias that the market
will, itself, get out of,

00:56:10.790 --> 00:56:12.480
which is where the
opportunity lies.

00:56:12.480 --> 00:56:14.940
Because you are
trying to buy it when

00:56:14.940 --> 00:56:16.410
the market still has that bias.

00:56:16.410 --> 00:56:19.645
And when the market doesn't, the
stock would have been rerated

00:56:19.645 --> 00:56:21.270
and you would have
made a lot of money.

00:56:21.270 --> 00:56:24.660
You see, the whole idea
in my work in investing

00:56:24.660 --> 00:56:26.140
in modern businesses,
what I found

00:56:26.140 --> 00:56:32.270
was the idea that moats can
only be found in some industries

00:56:32.270 --> 00:56:36.340
and never in other industries,
that itself is a prejudice.

00:56:36.340 --> 00:56:38.870
If you work hard enough,
even in businesses

00:56:38.870 --> 00:56:43.710
which have commodity labels,
you will find moated businesses,

00:56:43.710 --> 00:56:45.460
usually in niches.

00:56:45.460 --> 00:56:47.600
And when you find
them, you may often

00:56:47.600 --> 00:56:49.820
find that the market
is still treating them

00:56:49.820 --> 00:56:50.820
as a commodity business.

00:56:50.820 --> 00:56:52.630
That's the opportunity.

00:56:52.630 --> 00:56:55.030
AUDIENCE: So you spoke
about many value investors

00:56:55.030 --> 00:56:59.230
shying away from buying 25x
multiples and higher than that.

00:56:59.230 --> 00:57:03.610
And I think you also spoke about
intelligent fanatics and people

00:57:03.610 --> 00:57:07.620
who are driven and obsessed by
growth and returning profits.

00:57:07.620 --> 00:57:09.380
I guess the question
I have is, where

00:57:09.380 --> 00:57:12.870
does a healthy margin of
safety come into all of this.

00:57:12.870 --> 00:57:15.490
I think one of the reasons I
shy away from a 25x multiple

00:57:15.490 --> 00:57:18.179
is, what's my margin
of safety, right.

00:57:18.179 --> 00:57:20.220
I look at the previous
pace it's been trading at.

00:57:20.220 --> 00:57:21.292
I look at its growth.

00:57:21.292 --> 00:57:23.250
When I'm buying something
at a P/E value of 25,

00:57:23.250 --> 00:57:26.250
I'm expecting 10%, 15%
growth year-on-year

00:57:26.250 --> 00:57:28.730
for the next decade, right?

00:57:28.730 --> 00:57:31.210
So I just wanted to hear
your thoughts on that.

00:57:31.210 --> 00:57:32.110
SANJAY BAKSHI: Sure.

00:57:32.110 --> 00:57:33.570
I'll answer that in two parts.

00:57:33.570 --> 00:57:35.870
Firstly, when you think
about P/E multiple,

00:57:35.870 --> 00:57:38.820
the P part is obvious because
it's observed from the market.

00:57:38.820 --> 00:57:41.720
It's the E part which
is quite subjective.

00:57:41.720 --> 00:57:46.470
And I mentioned
this-- in my judgment,

00:57:46.470 --> 00:57:49.610
in many moated
businesses, the E part

00:57:49.610 --> 00:57:52.360
is higher than what you
see over there for reasons

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:53.520
that I explained.

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:55.020
And when you make
those adjustments,

00:57:55.020 --> 00:57:58.589
then what looks expensive
is not that expensive.

00:57:58.589 --> 00:57:59.130
It's cheaper.

00:57:59.130 --> 00:58:00.010
That's one.

00:58:00.010 --> 00:58:03.260
Secondly, if you look at a
business that generally has

00:58:03.260 --> 00:58:05.840
a moat-- that means it
has strong entry barriers

00:58:05.840 --> 00:58:07.640
and it has the ability
to compound capital

00:58:07.640 --> 00:58:11.810
at lucrative rates for
long periods of time--

00:58:11.810 --> 00:58:15.100
if you do the math, as
Charlie has mentioned,

00:58:15.100 --> 00:58:18.630
even if you pay a 25 P/E
multiple for a business which

00:58:18.630 --> 00:58:22.130
is compounding capital
internally at a fabulous rate

00:58:22.130 --> 00:58:24.730
and has reinvestment
opportunities,

00:58:24.730 --> 00:58:26.380
it's the duration
of the opportunity.

00:58:26.380 --> 00:58:29.990
If you extend that from five
years to 10 years, and from 10

00:58:29.990 --> 00:58:32.810
to a longer period if
you have that conviction,

00:58:32.810 --> 00:58:35.040
then it becomes
quite attractive.

00:58:35.040 --> 00:58:37.340
I think you may be
referring to some businesses

00:58:37.340 --> 00:58:40.290
in this part of the word where
the growth rates are actually

00:58:40.290 --> 00:58:42.240
lower.

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:45.480
Where I come from, growth
rates in many business

00:58:45.480 --> 00:58:46.590
are actually very high.

00:58:46.590 --> 00:58:50.370
They are sometimes in high
double-digit percentage

00:58:50.370 --> 00:58:51.410
numbers.

00:58:51.410 --> 00:58:56.420
