what you see on the books.

00:59:07.370 --> 00:59:11.340
So first of all, a company
could be doing well

00:59:11.340 --> 00:59:12.890
for 10 years, 20 years.

00:59:12.890 --> 00:59:14.510
And these are very,
very big numbers.

00:59:14.510 --> 00:59:17.400
Some company is doing
good for two decades.

00:59:17.400 --> 00:59:18.900
And eventually
something blows up.

00:59:18.900 --> 00:59:21.550
And what you figure out is
that was a very, very big fraud

00:59:21.550 --> 00:59:22.059
going on.

00:59:22.059 --> 00:59:24.600
It could be numbers, could be
because the auditors were being

00:59:24.600 --> 00:59:27.460
bribed and all those things.

00:59:27.460 --> 00:59:29.880
It happens more
in Asian countries

00:59:29.880 --> 00:59:32.060
than, probably, North America.

00:59:32.060 --> 00:59:34.689
SANJAY BAKSHI: Is
that a prejudice?

00:59:34.689 --> 00:59:35.480
AUDIENCE: Could be.

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:37.730
But when you're identifying
an individual company

00:59:37.730 --> 00:59:41.180
and you see returns
which far surpass

00:59:41.180 --> 00:59:45.980
the returns of other companies
in the same industry,

00:59:45.980 --> 00:59:48.494
one thing that one also
needs to scrutinize

00:59:48.494 --> 00:59:50.160
is, is there some
kind of a fraud that's

00:59:50.160 --> 00:59:50.965
going on over there.

00:59:50.965 --> 00:59:52.048
SANJAY BAKSHI: Absolutely.

00:59:52.048 --> 00:59:54.230
That's the whole point
of being an analyst is

00:59:54.230 --> 00:59:56.100
that you have to be skeptical.

00:59:56.100 --> 00:59:57.460
You have to have the diligence.

00:59:57.460 --> 00:59:59.405
You have to be able
to check the numbers.

00:59:59.405 --> 01:00:00.780
You have to do
background checks.

01:00:00.780 --> 01:00:01.650
There are a lot
of things that you

01:00:01.650 --> 01:00:03.930
need to do to make sure
that the numbers are right.

01:00:03.930 --> 01:00:05.410
If the numbers are not
right, then obviously

01:00:05.410 --> 01:00:07.159
you shouldn't be
investing in that anyway.

01:00:07.159 --> 01:00:09.460
Because if they
can cook the books,

01:00:09.460 --> 01:00:11.290
then you really don't
want to be a partner

01:00:11.290 --> 01:00:14.340
in a business run by a person
who is cooking the books,

01:00:14.340 --> 01:00:15.290
right?

01:00:15.290 --> 01:00:16.920
So I think it's
absolutely imperative

01:00:16.920 --> 01:00:18.072
that you do that test.

01:00:18.072 --> 01:00:20.030
And it doesn't matter
which country you are in.

01:00:20.030 --> 01:00:22.320
I think that there
was a Madoff here

01:00:22.320 --> 01:00:25.620
and there was an
Enron here as well.

01:00:25.620 --> 01:00:29.230
So it's something that
is a required discipline

01:00:29.230 --> 01:00:31.770
for any value investor,
to be able to do ascertain

01:00:31.770 --> 01:00:34.810
whether the numbers
are cooked or not.

